# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: zero-knowledge-proofs
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Hashing is a one-directional mathematical operation which is quick to calculate, yet hard to reverse.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] So password storage and digital signatures benefit from hashes.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Even a small change in the input results in a very different hash.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] So it is useful to check if two copies of data or software match.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Typically the operation works on a block of input data; the hash output is then hashed with the next block, creating a new hash reflecting everything to that point; again and again until the final hash reflects everything through the final block.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Cryptographic hash functions have many information-security applications, notably in digital signatures, message authentication codes (MACs), and other forms of authentication.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] They can also be used as ordinary hash functions, to index data in hash tables, for fingerprinting, to detect duplicate data or uniquely identify files, and as checksums to detect accidental data corruption.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Indeed, in information-security contexts, cryptographic hash values are sometimes called (*digital*) *fingerprints*, *checksums*, (*message*) *digests*, or just *hash values*, even though all these terms stand for more general functions with rather different properties and purposes.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Non-cryptographic hash functions are used in hash tables and to detect accidental errors; their constructions frequently provide no resistance to a deliberate attack.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] For example, a denial-of-service attack on hash tables is possible if the collisions are easy to find, as in the case of linear cyclic redundancy check (CRC) functions.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Most cryptographic hash functions are designed to take a string of any length as input and produce a fixed-length hash value.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] A cryptographic hash function must be able to withstand all known types of cryptanalytic attack.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Collision resistance implies second pre-image resistance but does not imply pre-image resistance.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] The weaker assumption is always preferred in theoretical cryptography, but in practice, a hash-function that is only second pre-image resistant is considered insecure and is therefore not recommended for real applications.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Informally, these properties mean that a malicious adversary cannot replace or modify the input data without changing its digest.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Thus, if two strings have the same digest, one can be very confident that they are identical.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Second pre-image resistance prevents an attacker from crafting a document with the same hash as a document the attacker cannot control.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Collision resistance prevents an attacker from creating two distinct documents with the same hash.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] A function meeting these criteria may still have undesirable properties.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Currently, popular cryptographic hash functions are vulnerable to *length-extension* attacks: given hash(*m*) and len(*m*) but not *m*, by choosing a suitable *m*′ an attacker can calculate hash(*m* ∥ *m*′), where ∥ denotes concatenation.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] This property can be used to break naive authentication schemes based on hash functions.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] The HMAC construction works around these problems.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] In practice, collision resistance is insufficient for many practical uses.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] In addition to collision resistance, it should be impossible for an adversary to find two messages with substantially similar digests; or to infer any useful information about the data, given only its digest.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] In particular, a hash function should behave as much as possible like a random function (often called a random oracle in proofs of security) while still being deterministic and efficiently computable.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] This rules out functions like the SWIFFT function, which can be rigorously proven to be collision-resistant assuming that certain problems on ideal lattices are computationally difficult, but, as a linear function, does not satisfy these additional properties.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Checksum algorithms, such as CRC-32 and other cyclic redundancy checks, are designed to meet much weaker requirements and are generally unsuitable as cryptographic hash functions.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] For example, a CRC was used for message integrity in the WEP encryption standard, but an attack was readily discovered, which exploited the linearity of the checksum.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] In cryptographic practice, "difficult" generally means "almost certainly beyond the reach of any adversary who must be prevented from breaking the system for as long as the security of the system is deemed important".
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] The meaning of the term is therefore somewhat dependent on the application since the effort that a malicious agent may put into the task is usually proportional to their expected gain.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] However, since the needed effort usually multiplies with the digest length, even a thousand-fold advantage in processing power can be neutralized by adding a dozen bits to the latter.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] For messages selected from a limited set of messages, for example passwords or other short messages, it can be feasible to invert a hash by trying all possible messages in the set.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Because cryptographic hash functions are typically designed to be computed quickly, special key derivation functions that require greater computing resources have been developed that make such brute-force attacks more difficult.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] In some theoretical analyses "difficult" has a specific mathematical meaning, such as "not solvable in asymptotic polynomial time".
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Such interpretations of *difficulty* are important in the study of provably secure cryptographic hash functions but do not usually have a strong connection to practical security.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] For example, an exponential-time algorithm can sometimes still be fast enough to make a feasible attack.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Conversely, a polynomial-time algorithm (e.g., one that requires *n*20 steps for *n*-digit keys) may be too slow for any practical use.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] An illustration of the potential use of a cryptographic hash is as follows: Alice poses a tough math problem to Bob and claims that she has solved it.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Bob would like to try it himself, but would yet like to be sure that Alice is not bluffing.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Therefore, Alice writes down her solution, computes its hash, and tells Bob the hash value (whilst keeping the solution secret).
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Then, when Bob comes up with the solution himself a few days later, Alice can prove that she had the solution earlier by revealing it and having Bob hash it and then check that it matches the hash value given to him before.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] An important application of secure hashes is the verification of message integrity.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Comparing message digests (hash digests over the message) calculated before, and after, transmission can determine whether any changes have been made to the message or file.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] MD5, SHA-1, or SHA-2 hash digests are sometimes published on websites or forums to allow verification of integrity for downloaded files, including files retrieved using file sharing such as mirroring.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] This practice establishes a chain of trust as long as the hashes are posted on a trusted site – usually the originating site – authenticated by HTTPS.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Using a cryptographic hash and a chain of trust detects malicious changes to the file.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Non-cryptographic error-detecting codes such as cyclic redundancy checks only prevent against *non-malicious* alterations of the file, since an intentional spoof can readily be crafted to have the colliding code value.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Almost all digital signature schemes require a cryptographic hash to be calculated over the message.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] This allows the signature calculation to be performed on the relatively small, statically sized hash digest.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] The message is considered authentic if the signature verification succeeds given the signature and recalculated hash digest over the message.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] So the message integrity property of the cryptographic hash is used to create secure and efficient digital signature schemes.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Password verification commonly relies on cryptographic hashes.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Storing all user passwords as cleartext can result in a massive security breach if the password file is compromised.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] One way to reduce this danger is to only store the hash digest of each password.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] To authenticate a user, the password presented by the user is hashed and compared with the stored hash.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] A password reset method is required when password hashing is performed; original passwords cannot be recalculated from the stored hash value.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] However, use of standard cryptographic hash functions, such as the SHA series, is no longer considered safe for password storage.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] These algorithms are designed to be computed quickly, so if the hashed values are compromised, it is possible to try guessed passwords at high rates.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Common graphics processing units can try billions of possible passwords each second.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Password hash functions that perform key stretching – such as PBKDF2, scrypt or Argon2 – commonly use repeated invocations of a cryptographic hash to increase the time (and in some cases computer memory) required to perform brute-force attacks on stored password hash digests.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] For details, see § Attacks on hashed passwords.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] A password hash also requires the use of a large random, non-secret salt value that can be stored with the password hash.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] The salt is hashed with the password, altering the password hash mapping for each password, thereby making it infeasible for an adversary to store tables of precomputed hash values to which the password hash digest can be compared or to test a large number of purloined hash values in parallel.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] A proof-of-work system (or protocol, or function) is an economic measure to deter denial-of-service attacks and other service abuses such as spam on a network by requiring some work from the service requester, usually meaning processing time by a computer.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] A key feature of these schemes is their asymmetry: the work must be moderately hard (but feasible) on the requester side but easy to check for the service provider.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] One popular system – used in Bitcoin mining and Hashcash – uses partial hash inversions to prove that work was done, to unlock a mining reward in Bitcoin, and as a good-will token to send an e-mail in Hashcash.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] The sender is required to find a message whose hash value begins with a number of zero bits.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] The average work that the sender needs to perform in order to find a valid message is exponential in the number of zero bits required in the hash value, while the recipient can verify the validity of the message by executing a single hash function.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] For instance, in Hashcash, a sender is asked to generate a header whose 160-bit SHA-1 hash value has the first 20 bits as zeros.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] The sender will, on average, have to try 219 times to find a valid header.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] A message digest can also serve as a means of reliably identifying a file; several source code management systems, including Git, Mercurial and Monotone, use the sha1sum of various types of content (file content, directory trees, ancestry information, etc.) to uniquely identify them.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Hashes are used to identify files on peer-to-peer filesharing networks.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] For example, in an ed2k link, an MD4-variant hash is combined with the file size, providing sufficient information for locating file sources, downloading the file, and verifying its contents.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Such file hashes are often the top hash of a hash list or a hash tree, which allows for additional benefits.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] One of the main applications of a hash function is to allow the fast look-up of data in a hash table.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Being hash functions of a particular kind, cryptographic hash functions lend themselves well to this application too.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] However, compared with standard hash functions, cryptographic hash functions tend to be much more expensive computationally.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Content-addressable storage (CAS), also referred to as content-addressed storage or fixed-content storage, is a way to store information so it can be retrieved based on its content, not its name or location.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] It has been used for high-speed storage and retrieval of fixed content, such as documents stored for compliance with government regulations.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Content-addressable storage is similar to content-addressable memory.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] CAS systems work by passing the content of the file through a cryptographic hash function to generate a unique key, the "content address".
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] The file system's directory stores these addresses and a pointer to the physical storage of the content.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Because an attempt to store the same file will generate the same key, CAS systems ensure that the files within them are unique, and because changing the file will result in a new key, CAS systems provide assurance that the file is unchanged.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] CAS became a significant market during the 2000s, especially after the introduction of the 2002 Sarbanes–Oxley Act in the United States which required the storage of enormous numbers of documents for long periods and retrieved only rarely.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Ever-increasing performance of traditional file systems and new software systems have eroded the value of legacy CAS systems, which have become increasingly rare after roughly 2018.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] However, the principles of content addressability continue to be of great interest to computer scientists, and form the core of numerous emerging technologies, such as peer-to-peer file sharing, cryptocurrencies, and distributed computing.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] There are several methods to use a block cipher to build a cryptographic hash function, specifically a one-way compression function.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] The methods resemble the block cipher modes of operation usually used for encryption.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Many well-known hash functions, including MD4, MD5, SHA-1 and SHA-2, are built from block-cipher-like components designed for the purpose, with feedback to ensure that the resulting function is not invertible.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-3 finalists included functions with block-cipher-like components (e.g., Skein, BLAKE) though the function finally selected, Keccak, was built on a cryptographic sponge instead.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] A standard block cipher such as AES can be used in place of these custom block ciphers; that might be useful when an embedded system needs to implement both encryption and hashing with minimal code size or hardware area.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] However, that approach can have costs in efficiency and security.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] The ciphers in hash functions are built for hashing: they use large keys and blocks, can efficiently change keys every block, and have been designed and vetted for resistance to related-key attacks.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] General-purpose ciphers tend to have different design goals.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] In particular, AES has key and block sizes that make it nontrivial to use to generate long hash values; AES encryption becomes less efficient when the key changes each block; and related-key attacks make it potentially less secure for use in a hash function than for encryption.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] A hash function must be able to process an arbitrary-length message into a fixed-length output.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] This can be achieved by breaking the input up into a series of equally sized blocks, and operating on them in sequence using a one-way compression function.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] The compression function can either be specially designed for hashing or be built from a block cipher.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] A hash function built with the Merkle–Damgård construction is as resistant to collisions as is its compression function; any collision for the full hash function can be traced back to a collision in the compression function.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] The last block processed should also be unambiguously length padded; this is crucial to the security of this construction.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] This construction is called the Merkle–Damgård construction.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Most common classical hash functions, including SHA-1 and MD5, take this form.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] A straightforward application of the Merkle–Damgård construction, where the size of hash output is equal to the internal state size (between each compression step), results in a **narrow-pipe** hash design.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] This design causes many inherent flaws, including length-extension, multicollisions, long message attacks, generate-and-paste attacks, and also cannot be parallelized.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] As a result, modern hash functions are built on **wide-pipe** constructions that have a larger internal state size – which range from tweaks of the Merkle–Damgård construction to new constructions such as the sponge construction and HAIFA construction.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] None of the entrants in the NIST hash function competition use a classical Merkle–Damgård construction.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Meanwhile, truncating the output of a longer hash, such as used in SHA-512/256, also defeats many of these attacks.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Hash functions can be used to build other cryptographic primitives.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] For these other primitives to be cryptographically secure, care must be taken to build them correctly.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Message authentication codes (MACs) (also called keyed hash functions) are often built from hash functions.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Just as block ciphers can be used to build hash functions, hash functions can be used to build block ciphers.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Luby-Rackoff constructions using hash functions can be provably secure if the underlying hash function is secure.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Also, many hash functions (including SHA-1 and SHA-2) are built by using a special-purpose block cipher in a Davies–Meyer or other construction.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] That cipher can also be used in a conventional mode of operation, without the same security guarantees; for example, SHACAL, BEAR and LION.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Pseudorandom number generators (PRNGs) can be built using hash functions.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] This is done by combining a (secret) random seed with a counter and hashing it.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Some hash functions, such as Skein, Keccak, and RadioGatún, output an arbitrarily long stream and can be used as a stream cipher, and stream ciphers can also be built from fixed-length digest hash functions.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Often this is done by first building a cryptographically secure pseudorandom number generator and then using its stream of random bytes as keystream.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] SEAL is a stream cipher that uses SHA-1 to generate internal tables, which are then used in a keystream generator more or less unrelated to the hash algorithm.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] SEAL is not guaranteed to be as strong (or weak) as SHA-1.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Similarly, the key expansion of the HC-128 and HC-256 stream ciphers makes heavy use of the SHA-256 hash function.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Concatenating outputs from multiple hash functions provide collision resistance as good as the strongest of the algorithms included in the concatenated result.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] For example, older versions of Transport Layer Security (TLS) and Secure Sockets Layer (SSL) used concatenated MD5 and SHA-1 sums.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] This ensures that a method to find collisions in one of the hash functions does not defeat data protected by both hash functions.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] For Merkle–Damgård construction hash functions, the concatenated function is as collision-resistant as its strongest component, but not more collision-resistant.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Antoine Joux observed that 2-collisions lead to *n*-collisions: if it is feasible for an attacker to find two messages with the same MD5 hash, then they can find as many additional messages with that same MD5 hash as they desire, with no greater difficulty.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Among those *n* messages with the same MD5 hash, there is likely to be a collision in SHA-1.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] The additional work needed to find the SHA-1 collision (beyond the exponential birthday search) requires only polynomial time.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] There are many cryptographic hash algorithms; this section lists a few algorithms that are referenced relatively often.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] A more extensive list can be found on the page containing a comparison of cryptographic hash functions.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] MD5 was designed by Ronald Rivest in 1991 to replace an earlier hash function, MD4, and was specified in 1992 as RFC 1321.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Collisions against MD5 can be calculated within seconds, which makes the algorithm unsuitable for most use cases where a cryptographic hash is required.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] MD5 produces a digest of 128 bits (16 bytes).
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] The original specification – now commonly called SHA-0 – of the algorithm was published in 1993 under the title Secure Hash Standard, FIPS PUB 180, by U.S. government standards agency NIST (National Institute of Standards and Technology).
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] It was withdrawn by the NSA shortly after publication and was superseded by the revised version, published in 1995 in FIPS PUB 180-1 and commonly designated SHA-1.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Collisions against the full SHA-1 algorithm can be produced using the shattered attack and the hash function should be considered broken.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-1 produces a hash digest of 160 bits (20 bytes).
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Documents may refer to SHA-1 as just "SHA", even though this may conflict with the other Secure Hash Algorithms such as SHA-0, SHA-2, and SHA-3.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] RIPEMD (RACE Integrity Primitives Evaluation Message Digest) is a family of cryptographic hash functions developed in Leuven, Belgium, by Hans Dobbertin, Antoon Bosselaers, and Bart Preneel at the COSIC research group at the Katholieke Universiteit Leuven, and first published in 1996.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] RIPEMD was based upon the design principles used in MD4 and is similar in performance to the more popular SHA-1.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] RIPEMD-160 has, however, not been broken.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] As the name implies, RIPEMD-160 produces a hash digest of 160 bits (20 bytes).
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Whirlpool is a cryptographic hash function designed by Vincent Rijmen and Paulo S.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Barreto, who first described it in 2000.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Whirlpool is based on a substantially modified version of the Advanced Encryption Standard (AES).
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Whirlpool produces a hash digest of 512 bits (64 bytes).
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-2 (Secure Hash Algorithm 2) is a set of cryptographic hash functions designed by the United States National Security Agency (NSA), first published in 2001.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] They are built using the Merkle–Damgård structure, from a one-way compression function itself built using the Davies–Meyer structure from a (classified) specialized block cipher.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-2 basically consists of two hash algorithms: SHA-256 and SHA-512.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-224 is a variant of SHA-256 with different starting values and truncated output.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-512 is more secure than SHA-256 and is commonly faster than SHA-256 on 64-bit machines such as AMD64.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] The output size in bits is given by the extension to the "SHA" name, so SHA-224 has an output size of 224 bits (28 bytes); SHA-256, 32 bytes; SHA-384, 48 bytes; and SHA-512, 64 bytes.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-3 (Secure Hash Algorithm 3) was released by NIST on August 5, 2015.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-3 is a subset of the broader cryptographic primitive family Keccak.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] The Keccak algorithm is the work of Guido Bertoni, Joan Daemen, Michael Peeters, and Gilles Van Assche.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Keccak is based on a sponge construction, which can also be used to build other cryptographic primitives such as a stream cipher.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-3 provides the same output sizes as SHA-2: 224, 256, 384, and 512 bits.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Configurable output sizes can also be obtained using the SHAKE-128 and SHAKE-256 functions.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Here the -128 and -256 extensions to the name imply the security strength of the function rather than the output size in bits.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] BLAKE2, an improved version of BLAKE, was announced on December 21, 2012.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] It was created by Jean-Philippe Aumasson, Samuel Neves, Zooko Wilcox-O'Hearn, and Christian Winnerlein with the goal of replacing the widely used but broken MD5 and SHA-1 algorithms.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] When run on 64-bit x64 and ARM architectures, BLAKE2b is faster than SHA-3, SHA-2, SHA-1, and MD5.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Although BLAKE and BLAKE2 have not been standardized as SHA-3 has, BLAKE2 has been used in many protocols including the Argon2 password hash, for the high efficiency that it offers on modern CPUs.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] As BLAKE was a candidate for SHA-3, BLAKE and BLAKE2 both offer the same output sizes as SHA-3 – including a configurable output size.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] BLAKE3, an improved version of BLAKE2, was announced on January 9, 2020.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] It was created by Jack O'Connor, Jean-Philippe Aumasson, Samuel Neves, and Zooko Wilcox-O'Hearn.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] BLAKE3 is a single algorithm, in contrast to BLAKE and BLAKE2, which are algorithm families with multiple variants.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] The BLAKE3 compression function is closely based on that of BLAKE2s, with the biggest difference being that the number of rounds is reduced from 10 to 7.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Internally, BLAKE3 is a Merkle tree, and it supports higher degrees of parallelism than BLAKE2.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] There is a long list of cryptographic hash functions but many have been found to be vulnerable and should not be used.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Even if a hash function has never been broken, a successful attack against a weakened variant may undermine the experts' confidence.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] For instance, in August 2004 collisions were found in several then-popular hash functions, including MD5.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] These weaknesses called into question the security of stronger algorithms derived from the weak hash functions – in particular, SHA-1 (a strengthened version of SHA-0), RIPEMD-128, and RIPEMD-160 (both strengthened versions of RIPEMD).
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] On August 12, 2004, Joux, Carribault, Lemuel, and Jalby announced a collision for the full SHA-0 algorithm.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Joux et al. accomplished this using a generalization of the Chabaud and Joux attack.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] They found that the collision had complexity 251 and took about 80,000 CPU hours on a supercomputer with 256 Itanium 2 processors – equivalent to 13 days of full-time use of the supercomputer.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] In February 2005, an attack on SHA-1 was reported that would find collision in about 269 hashing operations, rather than the 280 expected for a 160-bit hash function.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] In August 2005, another attack on SHA-1 was reported that would find collisions in 263 operations.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Other theoretical weaknesses of SHA-1 have been known, and in February 2017 Google announced a collision in SHA-1.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Security researchers recommend that new applications can avoid these problems by using later members of the SHA family, such as SHA-2, or using techniques such as randomized hashing that do not require collision resistance.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] A successful, practical attack broke MD5 (used within certificates for Transport Layer Security) in 2008.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Many cryptographic hashes are based on the Merkle–Damgård construction.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] All cryptographic hashes that directly use the full output of a Merkle–Damgård construction are vulnerable to length extension attacks.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] This makes the MD5, SHA-1, RIPEMD-160, Whirlpool, and the SHA-256 / SHA-512 hash algorithms all vulnerable to this specific attack.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-3, BLAKE2, BLAKE3, and the truncated SHA-2 variants are not vulnerable to this type of attack.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Rather than store plain user passwords, controlled-access systems frequently store the hash of each user's password in a file or database.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] When someone requests access, the password they submit is hashed and compared with the stored value.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] If the database is stolen (an all-too-frequent occurrence), the thief will only have the hash values, not the passwords.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Passwords may still be retrieved by an attacker from the hashes, because most people choose passwords in predictable ways.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Lists of common passwords are widely circulated and many passwords are short enough that even all possible combinations may be tested if calculation of the hash does not take too much time.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] The use of cryptographic salt prevents some attacks, such as building files of precomputing hash values, e.g. rainbow tables.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] But searches on the order of 100 billion tests per second are possible with high-end graphics processors, making direct attacks possible even with salt.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] The United States National Institute of Standards and Technology recommends storing passwords using special hashes called key derivation functions (KDFs) that have been created to slow brute force searches.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] Slow hashes include pbkdf2, bcrypt, scrypt, argon2, Balloon and some recent modes of Unix crypt.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/cryptographic-hash-function] For KDFs that perform multiple hashes to slow execution, NIST recommends an iteration count of 10,000 or more.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] The protocol is open source and based on CryptoNote v2, a concept described in a 2013 white paper authored by Nicolas van Saberhagen.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] Developers used this concept to design Monero, and deployed its mainnet in 2014.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] The Monero protocol includes various methods to obfuscate transaction details, though users can optionally share view keys for third-party auditing.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] Transactions are validated through a miner network running RandomX, a proof-of-work algorithm.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] The algorithm issues new coins to miners and was designed to be resistant against application-specific integrated circuit (ASIC) mining.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] Monero's privacy features have attracted cypherpunks and users desiring privacy measures not provided in other cryptocurrencies.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] A 2022 study in *FSI Digital Investigations* concluded "For now, Monero is untraceable.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] However, it is probably only a matter of time and effort before it changes." Due to its perceived untraceability Monero is gaining increased use in illicit activities such as money laundering, darknet markets, ransomware, cryptojacking, and other organized crime.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] Monero's roots trace back to CryptoNote v2, a cryptocurrency protocol first introduced in a white paper published by the presumed pseudonymous Nicolas van Saberhagen in October 2013.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] In the paper, the author described privacy and anonymity as "the most important aspects of electronic cash" and characterized bitcoin's traceability as a "critical flaw".
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] A Bitcointalk forum user known as "*thankful_for_today*" implemented these ideas into a coin they called BitMonero.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] However, other forum users disagreed with *thankful_for_today'*s direction for BitMonero and decided to fork it in 2014, leading to the creation of Monero.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] *Monero* translates to *coin* in Esperanto.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] The plural of monero ("moneroj") is likewise formed using Esperanto grammar.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] Both van Saberhagen and *thankful_for_today* remain anonymous.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] Monero has the third-largest community of developers, behind bitcoin and Ethereum.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] The protocol's lead maintainer was previously South African developer Riccardo Spagni.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] Much of the core development team chooses to remain anonymous.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] Monero's key features are those around privacy and anonymity.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] Even though it is a public and decentralized ledger, all transaction details are obfuscated.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] This contrasts to bitcoin, where all transaction details, user addresses, and wallet balances are public and transparent.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] These features have given Monero a loyal following among crypto anarchists, cypherpunks, and privacy advocates.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] The transaction outputs, or notes, of users sending Monero are obfuscated through ring signatures, which groups a sender's outputs with other decoy outputs.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] Encryption of transaction amounts began in 2017 with the implementation of ring confidential transactions (RingCTs).
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] Developers also implemented a zero-knowledge proof method, "Bulletproofs", which guarantee a transaction occurred without revealing its value.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] Monero recipients are protected through "stealth addresses", public keys generated by the sender that are untraceable to the receiver by a network observer.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] These privacy features are enforced on the network by default.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] Monero uses Dandelion++, a protocol which obscures the IP address of devices producing transactions.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] In April 2017, researchers highlighted three major threats to Monero users' privacy.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] The first relies on leveraging the ring signature size of zero, and ability to see the output amounts.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] The second, "Leveraging Output Merging", involves tracking transactions where two outputs belong to the same user, such as when they send funds to themselves ("churning").
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] Finally, "Temporal Analysis", shows that predicting the right output in a ring signature could potentially be easier than previously thought.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] In 2018, researchers presented possible vulnerabilities in a paper titled "An Empirical Analysis of Traceability in the Monero Blockchain".
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] In September 2020, the United States Internal Revenue Service's criminal investigation division (IRS-CI), posted a $625,000 bounty for contractors who could develop tools to help trace Monero, other privacy-enhanced cryptocurrencies, the Bitcoin Lightning Network, or other "layer 2" protocol.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] The contract was awarded to blockchain analysis groups Chainalysis and Integra FEC.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] In 2021, researchers presented a transaction-flooding attack against Monero’s transaction-graph privacy at the IEEE International Conference on Blockchain and Cryptocurrency.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] Under specific assumptions about transaction structure and fees, the "FloodXMR" attack modelled how an adversary who floods the blockchain with their own transactions could, over time, deanonymize a substantial fraction of new transaction inputs at relatively low cost.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] Monero uses a proof-of-work algorithm, RandomX, to validate transactions.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] The method was introduced in November 2019 to replace the former algorithm CryptoNightR.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] Both algorithms were designed to be resistant to ASIC mining, which is commonly used to mine other cryptocurrencies such as bitcoin.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] Monero's privacy features have made it popular for illicit purposes.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] On-chain data from 2024 and 2025 shows that Monero’s transaction volumes remained significantly higher than in the 2020–2021 period, stabilizing at an elevated baseline that indicates sustained, regular demand rather than temporary speculation.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] After a wave of cryptocurrency exchange delistings in 2024–2025, Monero trading migrated to decentralized and peer-to-peer platforms, demonstrating resilient usage and ongoing demand.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] Monero's privacy features have made it the dominant cryptocurrency on darknet markets (DNMs), where anonymity is critical for both buyers and sellers.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] Unlike Bitcoin, whose public ledger enables traceable blockchain analysis, Monero obscures sender, receiver, and transaction amounts by default.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] In August 2016, dark market AlphaBay permitted its vendors to start accepting Monero as an alternative to bitcoin.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] The site was taken offline by law enforcement in 2017, but it was relaunched in 2021 with Monero as the sole permitted currency.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] A 2024 report covered by *Wired* found that vendors of child sexual abuse material increasingly used Monero for laundering proceeds through instant exchangers, with blockchain analysis firm Chainalysis describing Monero as "the currency of choice" for this purpose.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] By 2025, nearly half of newly launched darknet markets operated exclusively with Monero, a sharp increase from earlier years, driven by law enforcement advances in tracing Bitcoin and stablecoins.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] This trend has created a perception that markets relying solely on Bitcoin are less secure, pushing users toward Monero-only platforms that better protect against financial surveillance.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] A prominent example was White House Market, a darknet marketplace active from 2019 to 2021 that was used to traffic fentanyl and cocaine; the platform handled transactions in Monero and was referenced in multiple federal indictments.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] The market's closure did not halt the broader shift, as subsequent DNMs increasingly adopted Monero-only models that users deem more trustworthy because of the difficulty of tracing XMR payments.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] The United States Department of Justice and the Treasury Department have identified Monero as a frequently used tool in darknet and ransomware-related money laundering, with sanctioned exchangers processing hundreds of millions of dollars in XMR.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] In late 2017, malware and antivirus service providers blocked Coinhive, a JavaScript implementation of a Monero miner that was embedded in websites and apps, in some cases by hackers.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] Coinhive wrote the script as an alternative to advertisements; a website or app could embed it, and use website visitors' CPU to mine the cryptocurrency while the visitor is consuming the content of the webpage, with the site or app owner getting a percentage of the mined coins.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] Some websites and apps did this without informing visitors, or in some cases using all possible system resources.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] As a result, the script was blocked by companies offering ad blocking subscription lists, antivirus services, and antimalware services.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] Coinhive had been previously found hidden in *Showtime-*owned streaming platforms and Starbucks Wi-Fi hotspots in Argentina.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] Researchers in 2018 found similar malware that mined Monero and sent it to Kim Il-sung University in North Korea.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] Monero is sometimes used by ransomware groups.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] According to CNBC, in the first half of 2018, Monero was used in 44% of cryptocurrency ransomware attacks.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] The perpetrators of the 2017 WannaCry ransomware attack, which was attributed by the US government to North Korean threat actors, attempted to exchange the ransom they collected in Bitcoin to Monero.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] *Ars Technica* and *Fast Company* reported that the exchange was successful, but BBC News reported that the service the criminals attempted to use, ShapeShift, denied any such transfer.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] The Shadow Brokers, who leaked the exploits which were subsequently used in WannaCry but are unlikely to have been involved in the attack, began accepting Monero as payment later in 2017.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] In 2021, CNBC, the *Financial Times*, and *Newsweek* reported that demand for Monero was increasing following the recovery of a bitcoin ransom paid in the Colonial Pipeline cyber attack.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] The May 2021 hack forced the pipeline to pay a $4.4M ransom in bitcoin, though a large portion was recovered by the United States federal government the following month.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] The group behind the attack, DarkSide, normally requests payment in either bitcoin or Monero, but charge a 10–20% premium for payments made in bitcoin due to its increased traceability risk.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] Ransomware group REvil removed the option of paying ransom in bitcoin in 2021, demanding only Monero.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] Ransomware negotiators, groups that help victims pay ransoms, have contacted Monero developers to understand the technology.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] Despite this, CNBC reported that bitcoin was still the currency of choice demanded in most ransomware attacks, as insurers refuse to pay Monero ransom payments because of traceability concerns.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] The attribution of Monero to illicit markets has influenced some exchanges to forgo listing it.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] This has made it more difficult for users to exchange Monero for fiat currencies or other cryptocurrencies.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] Exchanges in South Korea and Australia have delisted Monero and other privacy coins due to regulatory pressure.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] In 2018, Europol and its director Rob Wainwright wrote that the year would see criminals shift from using bitcoin to using Monero, as well as Ethereum, Dash, and Zcash.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] *Bloomberg* and CNN reported that this demand for Monero was because authorities were becoming better at monitoring the Bitcoin blockchain.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] On 20 February 2024, the cryptocurrency exchange Binance delisted Monero, citing regulatory compliance.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/monero] The United States Internal Revenue Service (IRS) has offered funding for contractors that can develop Monero tracing technologies.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] Public key algorithms are fundamental security primitives in modern cryptosystems, including applications and protocols that offer assurance of the confidentiality and authenticity of electronic communications and data storage.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] They underpin numerous Internet standards, such as Transport Layer Security (TLS), SSH, S/MIME, and PGP.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] Compared to symmetric cryptography, public-key cryptography can be too slow for many purposes, so these protocols often combine symmetric cryptography with public-key cryptography in hybrid cryptosystems.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] Before the mid-1970s, all cipher systems used symmetric key algorithms, in which the same cryptographic key is used with the underlying algorithm by both the sender and the recipient, who must both keep the key secret.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] Of necessity, the key in every such system had to be exchanged between the communicating parties in some secure way prior to any use of the system – for instance, via a secure channel.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] This requirement is never trivial and very rapidly becomes unmanageable as the number of participants increases, when secure channels are not available, or when (as is sensible cryptographic practice) keys are frequently changed.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] In particular, if messages are meant to be secure from other users, a separate key is required for each possible pair of users.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] By contrast, in a public-key cryptosystem, the public keys can be disseminated widely and openly, and only the corresponding private keys need be kept secret.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] For example, a software publisher can create a signature key pair and include the public key in software installed on computers.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] Later, the publisher can distribute an update to the software signed using the private key, and any computer receiving an update can confirm it is genuine by verifying the signature using the public key.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] As long as the software publisher keeps the private key secret, even if a forger can distribute malicious updates to computers, they cannot convince the computers that any malicious updates are genuine.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] For example, a journalist can publish the public key of an encryption key pair on a website so that sources can send secret messages to the news organization in ciphertext.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] Only the journalist who knows the corresponding private key can decrypt the ciphertexts to obtain the sources' messages—an eavesdropper reading email on its way to the journalist cannot decrypt the ciphertexts.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] However, public-key encryption does not conceal metadata like what computer a source used to send a message, when they sent it, or how long it is.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] Public-key encryption on its own also does not tell the recipient anything about who sent a message—it just conceals the content of the message.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] Applications built on public-key cryptography include authenticating web servers with TLS, digital cash, password-authenticated key agreement, authenticating and concealing email content with OpenPGP or S/MIME, and time-stamping services and non-repudiation protocols.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] One important issue is confidence or proof that a particular public key is authentic, i.e., that it is correct and belongs to the person or entity claimed, and has not been tampered with or replaced by some (perhaps malicious) third party.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] A public key infrastructure (PKI), in which one or more third parties, known as certificate authorities, certify ownership of key pairs.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] This implies that the PKI system (software, hardware, and management) can be trusted by all involved.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] A web of trust decentralizes authentication by using individual endorsements of links between a user and their public key.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] PGP uses this approach, in addition to lookup in the domain name system (DNS).
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] The DKIM system for digitally signing emails also uses this approach.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] PGP, SSH, and the SSL/TLS family of schemes use this procedure; they are thus called hybrid cryptosystems.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] As with all security-related systems, there are various potential weaknesses in public-key cryptography.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] Aside from poor choice of an asymmetric key algorithm (there are few that are widely regarded as satisfactory) or too short a key length, the chief security risk is that the private key of a pair becomes known.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] All security of messages, authentication, etc., encrypted with this private key will then be lost.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] This is commonly mitigated (such as in recent TLS schemes) by using Forward secrecy capable schemes that generate an ephemeral set of keys during the communication which must also be known for the communication to be compromised.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] Additionally, with the advent of quantum computing, many asymmetric key algorithms are considered vulnerable to attacks, and new quantum-resistant schemes are being developed to overcome the problem.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] Beyond algorithmic or key-length weaknesses, some studies have noted risks when private key control is delegated to third parties.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] Research on Uruguay’s implementation of Public Key Infrastructure under Law 18.600 found that centralized key custody by Trust Service Providers (TSPs) may weaken the principle of private-key secrecy, increasing exposure to man-in-the-middle attacks and raising concerns about legal non-repudiation.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] All public key schemes are in theory susceptible to a "brute-force key search attack".
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] However, such an attack is impractical if the amount of computation needed to succeed – termed the "work factor" by Claude Shannon – is out of reach of all potential attackers.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] In many cases, the work factor can be increased by simply choosing a longer key.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] But other algorithms may inherently have much lower work factors, making resistance to a brute-force attack (e.g., from longer keys) irrelevant.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] Some special and specific algorithms have been developed to aid in attacking some public key encryption algorithms; both RSA and ElGamal encryption have known attacks that are much faster than the brute-force approach.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] None of these are sufficiently improved to be actually practical, however.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] Major weaknesses have been found for several formerly promising asymmetric key algorithms.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] The "knapsack packing" algorithm was found to be insecure after the development of a new attack.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] As with all cryptographic functions, public-key implementations may be vulnerable to side-channel attacks that exploit information leakage to simplify the search for a secret key.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] These are often independent of the algorithm being used.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] Research is underway to both discover, and to protect against, new attacks.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] Another potential security vulnerability in using asymmetric keys is the possibility of a "man-in-the-middle" attack, in which the communication of public keys is intercepted by a third party (the "man in the middle") and then modified to provide different public keys instead.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] Encrypted messages and responses must, in all instances, be intercepted, decrypted, and re-encrypted by the attacker using the correct public keys for the different communication segments so as to avoid suspicion.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] A communication is said to be insecure where data is transmitted in a manner that allows for interception (also called "sniffing").
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] These terms refer to reading the sender's private data in its entirety.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] A communication is particularly unsafe when interceptions can not be prevented or monitored by the sender.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] A man-in-the-middle attack can be difficult to implement due to the complexities of modern security protocols.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] However, the task becomes simpler when a sender is using insecure media such as public networks, the Internet, or wireless communication.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] In these cases an attacker can compromise the communications infrastructure rather than the data itself.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] A hypothetical malicious staff member at an Internet service provider (ISP) might find a man-in-the-middle attack relatively straightforward.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] Capturing the public key would only require searching for the key as it gets sent through the ISP's communications hardware; in properly implemented asymmetric key schemes, this is not a significant risk.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] In some advanced man-in-the-middle attacks, one side of the communication will see the original data while the other will receive a malicious variant.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] Asymmetric man-in-the-middle attacks can prevent users from realizing their connection is compromised.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] This remains so even when one user's data is known to be compromised because the data appears fine to the other user.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] This can lead to confusing disagreements between users such as "it must be on your end!" when neither user is at fault.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] Hence, man-in-the-middle attacks are only fully preventable when the communications infrastructure is physically controlled by one or both parties; such as via a wired route inside the sender's own building.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] In summation, public keys are easier to alter when the communications hardware used by a sender is controlled by an attacker.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] One approach to prevent such attacks involves the use of a public key infrastructure (PKI); a set of roles, policies, and procedures needed to create, manage, distribute, use, store and revoke digital certificates and manage public-key encryption.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] Web browsers, for instance, are supplied with a long list of "self-signed identity certificates" from PKI providers – these are used to check the *bona fides* of the certificate authority and then, in a second step, the certificates of potential communicators.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] An attacker who could subvert one of those certificate authorities into issuing a certificate for a bogus public key could then mount a "man-in-the-middle" attack as easily as if the certificate scheme were not used at all.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] An attacker who penetrates an authority's servers and obtains its store of certificates and keys (public and private) would be able to spoof, masquerade, decrypt, and forge transactions without limit, assuming that they were able to place themselves in the communication stream.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] Despite its theoretical and potential problems, Public key infrastructure is widely used.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] Examples include TLS and its predecessor SSL, which are commonly used to provide security for web browser transactions (for example, most websites utilize TLS for HTTPS).
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] Aside from the resistance to attack of a particular key pair, the security of the certification hierarchy must be considered when deploying public key systems.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] Some certificate authority – usually a purpose-built program running on a server computer – vouches for the identities assigned to specific private keys by producing a digital certificate.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] Public key digital certificates are typically valid for several years at a time, so the associated private keys must be held securely over that time.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] When a private key used for certificate creation higher in the PKI server hierarchy is compromised, or accidentally disclosed, then a "man-in-the-middle attack" is possible, making any subordinate certificate wholly insecure.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] Most of the available public-key encryption software does not conceal metadata in the message header, which might include the identities of the sender and recipient, the sending date, subject field, and the software they use etc.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] Rather, only the body of the message is concealed and can only be decrypted with the private key of the intended recipient.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] This means that a third party could construct quite a detailed model of participants in a communication network, along with the subjects being discussed, even if the message body itself is hidden.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] However, there has been a recent demonstration of messaging with encrypted headers, which obscures the identities of the sender and recipient, and significantly reduces the available metadata to a third party.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] The concept is based around an open repository containing separately encrypted metadata blocks and encrypted messages.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] Only the intended recipient is able to decrypt the metadata block, and having done so they can identify and download their messages and decrypt them.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] Such a messaging system is at present in an experimental phase and not yet deployed.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] Scaling this method would reveal to the third party only the inbox server being used by the recipient and the timestamp of sending and receiving.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] The server could be shared by thousands of users, making social network modelling much more challenging.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] During the early history of cryptography, two parties would rely upon a key that they would exchange by means of a secure, but non-cryptographic, method such as a face-to-face meeting, or a trusted courier.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] This key, which both parties must then keep absolutely secret, could then be used to exchange encrypted messages.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] A number of significant practical difficulties arise with this approach to distributing keys.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] Here he described the relationship of one-way functions to cryptography, and went on to discuss specifically the factorization problem used to create a trapdoor function.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] Ellis, a British cryptographer at the UK Government Communications Headquarters (GCHQ), conceived of the possibility of "non-secret encryption", (now called public key cryptography), but could see no way to implement it.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] In 1973, his colleague Clifford Cocks implemented what has become known as the RSA encryption algorithm, giving a practical method of "non-secret encryption", and in 1974 another GCHQ mathematician and cryptographer, Malcolm J.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] Williamson, developed what is now known as Diffie–Hellman key exchange.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] The scheme was also passed to the US's National Security Agency.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] Both organisations had a military focus and only limited computing power was available in any case; the potential of public key cryptography remained unrealised by either organization.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] These discoveries were not publicly acknowledged until the research was declassified by the British government in 1997.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] In 1976, an asymmetric key cryptosystem was published by Whitfield Diffie and Martin Hellman who, influenced by Ralph Merkle's work on public key distribution, disclosed a method of public key agreement.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] This method of key exchange, which uses exponentiation in a finite field, came to be known as Diffie–Hellman key exchange.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] This was the first published practical method for establishing a shared secret-key over an authenticated (but not confidential) communications channel without using a prior shared secret.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] Merkle's "public key-agreement technique" became known as Merkle's Puzzles, and was invented in 1974 and only published in 1978.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] This makes asymmetric encryption a rather new field in cryptography although cryptography itself dates back more than 2,000 years.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] In 1977, a generalization of Cocks's scheme was independently invented by Ron Rivest, Adi Shamir and Leonard Adleman, all then at MIT.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] The latter authors published their work in 1978 in Martin Gardner's Scientific American column, and the algorithm came to be known as RSA, from their initials.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] RSA uses exponentiation modulo a product of two very large primes, to encrypt and decrypt, performing both public key encryption and public key digital signatures.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] Its security is connected to the extreme difficulty of factoring large integers, a problem for which there is no known efficient general technique.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] A description of the algorithm was published in the Mathematical Games column in the August 1977 issue of Scientific American.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] Since the 1970s, a large number and variety of encryption, digital signature, key agreement, and other techniques have been developed, including the Rabin signature, ElGamal encryption, DSA and ECC.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] In addition to the algorithms developed within the open academic and standards communities, several countries have developed national public-key cryptography standards for use within their jurisdictions.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/public-key-cryptography] These include SM2 and SM9 (China), GOST R 34.10-2012 (Russia), EC-KCDSA (South Korea), and DSTU 4145 (Ukraine).
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] Zero-knowledge rollups (ZK-rollups) are layer 2 scaling solutions that increase throughput on Ethereum Mainnet by moving computation and state-storage offchain.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] ZK-rollups can process thousands of transactions in a batch and then only post some minimal summary data to Mainnet.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] This summary data defines the changes that should be made to the Ethereum state and some cryptographic proof that those changes are correct.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] You should have read and understood our page on Ethereum scaling and layer 2.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] The ZK-rollup's state is maintained by a smart contract deployed on the Ethereum network.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] To update this state, ZK-rollup nodes must submit a validity proof for verification.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] As mentioned, the validity proof is a cryptographic assurance that the state-change proposed by the rollup is really the result of executing the given batch of transactions.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] This means that ZK-rollups only need to provide validity proofs to finalize transactions on Ethereum instead of posting all transaction data onchain like optimistic rollups.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] There are no delays when moving funds from a ZK-rollup to Ethereum because exit transactions are executed once the ZK-rollup contract verifies the validity proof.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] Conversely, withdrawing funds from optimistic rollups is subject to a delay to allow anyone to challenge the exit transaction with a .
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] ZK-rollups write transactions to Ethereum as `calldata`.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] `calldata` is where data that is included in external calls to smart contract functions gets stored.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] Information in `calldata` is published on the blockchain, allowing anyone to reconstruct the rollup’s state independently.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] ZK-rollups use compression techniques to reduce transaction data—for example, accounts are represented by an index rather than an address, which saves 28 bytes of data.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] Onchain data publication is a significant cost for rollups, so data compression can reduce fees for users.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] A ZK-rollup chain is an offchain protocol that operates on top of the Ethereum blockchain and is managed by onchain Ethereum smart contracts.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] ZK-rollups execute transactions outside of Mainnet, but periodically commit offchain transaction batches to an onchain rollup contract.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] This transaction record is immutable, much like the Ethereum blockchain, and forms the ZK-rollup chain.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] **Offchain virtual machine (VM)**: While the ZK-rollup protocol lives on Ethereum, transaction execution and state storage happen on a separate virtual machine independent of the EVM.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] This offchain VM is the execution environment for transactions on the ZK-rollup and serves as the secondary layer or "layer 2" for the ZK-rollup protocol.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] Validity proofs verified on Ethereum Mainnet guarantee the correctness of state transitions in the offchain VM.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] ZK-rollups are "hybrid scaling solutions"—offchain protocols that operate independently but derive security from Ethereum.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] Specifically, the Ethereum network enforces the validity of state updates on the ZK-rollup and guarantees the availability of data behind every update to the rollup's state.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] As a result, ZK-rollups are considerably safer than pure offchain scaling solutions, such as sidechains, which are responsible for their security properties, or validiums, which also verify transactions on Ethereum with validity proofs, but store transaction data elsewhere.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] ZK-rollups publish state data for every transaction processed offchain to Ethereum.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] With this data, it is possible for individuals or businesses to reproduce the rollup’s state and validate the chain themselves.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] Ethereum makes this data available to all participants of the network as `calldata`.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] ZK-rollups don’t need to publish much transaction data onchain because validity proofs already verify the authenticity of state transitions.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] Nevertheless, storing data onchain is still important because it allows permissionless, independent verification of the L2 chain's state which in turn allows anyone to submit batches of transactions, preventing malicious operators from censoring or freezing the chain.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] Onchain is required for users to interact with the rollup.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] Without access to state data users cannot query their account balance or initiate transactions (e.g., withdrawals) that rely on state information.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] Ethereum acts as a settlement layer for ZK-rollups: L2 transactions are finalized only if the L1 contract accepts the validity proof.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] This eliminates the risk of malicious operators corrupting the chain (e.g., stealing rollup funds) since every transaction must be approved on Mainnet.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] Also, Ethereum guarantees that user operations cannot be reversed once finalized on L1.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] Most ZK-rollups use a "supernode" (the operator) to execute transactions, produce batches, and submit blocks to L1.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] While this ensures efficiency, it increases the risk of censorship: malicious ZK-rollup operators can censor users by refusing to include their transactions in batches.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] As a security measure, ZK-rollups allow users to submit transactions directly to the rollup contract on Mainnet if they think they are being censored by the operator.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] This allows users to force an exit from the ZK-rollup to Ethereum without having to rely on the operator’s permission.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] Users in the ZK-rollup sign transactions and submit to L2 operators for processing and inclusion in the next batch.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] In some cases, the operator is a centralized entity, called a sequencer, who executes transactions, aggregates them into batches, and submits to L1.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] The sequencer in this system is the only entity allowed to produce L2 blocks and add rollup transactions to the ZK-rollup contract.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] Other ZK-rollups may rotate the operator role by using a proof-of-stake validator set.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] Prospective operators deposit funds in the rollup contract, with the size of each stake influencing the staker’s chances of getting selected to produce the next rollup batch.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] The operator’s stake can be slashed if they act maliciously, which incentivizes them to post valid blocks.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] As explained, transaction data is published on Ethereum as `calldata`.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] `calldata` is a data area in a smart contract used to pass arguments to a function and behaves similarly to memory.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] While `calldata` isn’t stored as part of Ethereum’s state, it persists onchain as part of the Ethereum chain's history logs (opens in a new tab).
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] `calldata` does not affect Ethereum's state, making it a cheap way to store data onchain.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] The `calldata` keyword often identifies the smart contract method being called by a transaction and holds inputs to the method in the form of an arbitrary sequence of bytes.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] ZK-rollups use `calldata` to publish compressed transaction data onchain; the rollup operator simply adds a new batch by calling the required function in the rollup contract and passes the compressed data as function arguments.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] This helps reduce costs for users since a large part of rollup fees go toward storing transaction data onchain.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] The ZK-rollup’s state, which includes L2 accounts and balances, is represented as a Merkle tree.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] A cryptographic hash of the Merkle tree’s root (Merkle root) is stored in the onchain contract, allowing the rollup protocol to track changes in the state of the ZK-rollup.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] The rollup transitions to a new state after the execution of a new set of transactions.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] The operator who initiated the state transition is required to compute a new state root and submit to the onchain contract.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] If the validity proof associated with the batch is authenticated by the verifier contract, the new Merkle root becomes the ZK-rollup’s canonical state root.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] Besides computing state roots, the ZK-rollup operator also creates a batch root—the root of a Merkle tree comprising all transactions in a batch.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] When a new batch is submitted, the rollup contract stores the batch root, allowing users to prove a transaction (e.g., a withdrawal request) was included in the batch.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] Users will have to provide transaction details, the batch root, and a Merkle proof showing the inclusion path.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] The new state root that the ZK-rollup operator submits to the L1 contract is the result of updates to the rollup’s state.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] Say Alice sends 10 tokens to Bob, the operator simply decreases Alice’s balance by 10 and increments Bob’s balance by 10.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] The operator then hashes the updated account data, rebuilds the rollup's Merkle tree, and submits the new Merkle root to the onchain contract.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] But the rollup contract won’t automatically accept the proposed state commitment until the operator proves the new Merkle root resulted from correct updates to the rollup’s state.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] The ZK-rollup operator does this by producing a validity proof, a succinct cryptographic commitment verifying the correctness of batched transactions.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] Validity proofs allow parties to prove the correctness of a statement without revealing the statement itself—hence, they are also called zero-knowledge proofs.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] ZK-rollups use validity proofs to confirm the correctness of offchain state transitions without having to re-execute transactions on Ethereum.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] These proofs can come in the form of a ZK-SNARK (opens in a new tab) (Zero-Knowledge Succinct Non-Interactive Argument of Knowledge) or ZK-STARK (opens in a new tab) (Zero-Knowledge Scalable Transparent Argument of Knowledge).
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] Both SNARKs and STARKs help attest to the integrity of offchain computation in ZK-rollups, although each proof type has distinctive features.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] For the ZK-SNARK protocol to work, creating a Common Reference String (CRS) is necessary: the CRS provides public parameters for proving and verifying validity proofs.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] The security of the proving system depends on the CRS setup; if information used to create public parameters fall into the possession of malicious actors they may be able to generate false validity proofs.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] Some ZK-rollups attempt to solve this problem by using a multi-party computation ceremony (MPC) (opens in a new tab), involving trusted individuals, to generate public parameters for the ZK-SNARK circuit.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] Each party contributes some randomness (called "toxic waste") to the construct the CRS, which they must destroy immediately.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] Trusted setups are used because they increase the security of the CRS setup.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] As long as one honest participant destroys their input, the security of the ZK-SNARK system is guaranteed.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] Still, this approach requires trusting those involved to delete their sampled randomness and not undermine the system's security guarantees.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] Trust assumptions aside, ZK-SNARKs are popular for their small proof sizes and constant-time verification.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] As proof verification on L1 constitutes the larger cost of operating a ZK-rollup, L2s use ZK-SNARKs to generate proofs that can be verified quickly and cheaply on Mainnet.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] Like ZK-SNARKs, ZK-STARKs prove the validity of offchain computation without revealing the inputs.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] However, ZK-STARKs are considered an improvement on ZK-SNARKs because of their scalability and transparency.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] ZK-STARKs are 'transparent', as they can work without the trusted setup of a Common Reference String (CRS).
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] Instead, ZK-STARKs rely on publicly verifiable randomness to set up parameters for generating and verifying proofs.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] ZK-STARKs also provide more scalability because the time needed to prove and verify validity proofs increases *quasilinearly* in relation to the complexity of the underlying computation.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] With ZK-SNARKs, proving and verification times scale *linearly* in relation to the size of the underlying computation.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] This means ZK-STARKs require less time than ZK-SNARKs for proving and verifying when large datasets are involved, making them useful for high-volume applications.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] ZK-STARKs are also secure against quantum computers, while the Elliptic Curve Cryptography (ECC) used in ZK-SNARKs is widely believed to be susceptible to quantum computing attacks.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] The downside to ZK-STARKs is that they produce larger proof sizes, which are more expensive to verify on Ethereum.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] Before accepting transactions, the operator will perform the usual checks.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] Once the ZK-rollup node has enough transactions, it aggregates them into a batch and compiles inputs for the proving circuit to compile into a succinct ZK-proof.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] The proving circuit computes the validity proof by "looping" over each transaction and performing the same checks the operator completed before processing the transaction.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] First, it verifies the sender's account is part of the existing state root using the provided Merkle proof.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] Then it reduces the sender's balance, increases their nonce, hashes the updated account data and combines it with the Merkle proof to generate a new Merkle root.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] This Merkle root reflects the sole change in the ZK-rollup's state: a change in the sender's balance and nonce.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] This is possible because the Merkle proof used to prove the account's existence is used to derive the new state root.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] The proving circuit performs the same process on the receiver's account.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] It checks if the receiver's account exists under the intermediate state root (using the Merkle proof), increases their balance, re-hashes the account data and combines it with the Merkle proof to generate a new state root.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] The process repeats for every transaction; each "loop" creates a new state root from updating the sender's account and a subsequent new root from updating the receiver's account.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] As explained, every update to the state root represents one part of the rollup's state tree changing.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] The ZK-proving circuit iterates over the entire transaction batch, verifying the sequence of updates that result in a final state root after the last transaction is executed.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] The last Merkle root computed becomes the newest canonical state root of the ZK-rollup.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] After the proving circuit verifies the correctness of state updates, the L2 operator submits the computed validity proof to the verifier contract on L1.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] If the proof satisfies the circuit (i.e., it is valid), it means that there exists a sequence of valid transactions that transition the rollup from the previous state (cryptographically fingerprinted by the pre-state root) to a new state (cryptographically fingerprinted by the post-state root).
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] If the pre-state root matches the root stored in the rollup contract, and the proof is valid, the rollup contract takes the post-state root from the proof and updates its state tree to reflect the rollup's changed state.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] Users enter the ZK-rollup by depositing tokens in the rollup's contract deployed on the L1 chain.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] This transaction is queued up since only operators can submit transactions to the rollup contract.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] If the pending deposit queue starts filling up, the ZK-rollup operator will take the deposit transactions and submit them to the rollup contract.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] Once the user's funds are in the rollup, they can start transacting by sending transactions to the operator for processing.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] Users can verify balances on the rollup by hashing their account data, sending the hash to the rollup contract, and providing a Merkle proof to verify against the current state root.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] Withdrawing from a ZK-rollup to L1 is straightforward.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] The user initiates the exit transaction by sending their assets on the rollup to a specified account for burning.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] If the operator includes the transaction in the next batch, the user can submit a withdrawal request to the onchain contract.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] The rollup contract hashes the transaction data, checks if the batch root exists, and uses the Merkle proof to check if the transaction hash is part of the batch root.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] Afterward, the contract executes the exit transaction and sends funds to the user's chosen address on L1.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] Unlike optimistic rollups, ZK-rollups are not readily compatible with the Ethereum Virtual Machine (EVM).
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] Proving general-purpose EVM computation in circuits is more difficult and resource-intensive than proving simple computations (like the token transfer described previously).
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] However, advances in zero-knowledge technology (opens in a new tab) are igniting renewed interest in wrapping EVM computation in zero-knowledge proofs.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] These efforts are geared towards creating a zero-knowledge EVM (zkEVM) implementation that can efficiently verify the correctness of program execution.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] A zkEVM recreates existing EVM opcodes for proving/verification in circuits, allowing to execute smart contracts.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] Like the EVM, a zkEVM transitions between states after computation is performed on some inputs.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] The difference is that the zkEVM also creates zero-knowledge proofs to verify the correctness of every step in the program’s execution.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] Validity proofs could verify the correctness of operations that touch the VM’s state (memory, stack, storage) and the computation itself (i.e., did the operation call the right opcodes and execute them correctly?).
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] The introduction of EVM-compatible ZK-rollups is expected to help developers leverage the scalability and security guarantees of zero-knowledge proofs.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] More importantly, compatibility with native Ethereum infrastructure means developers can build ZK-friendly dapps using familiar (and battle-tested) tooling and languages.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] How much users pay for transactions on ZK-rollups is dependent on the gas fee, just like on Ethereum Mainnet.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] **Data publication**: ZK-rollups publish state data for every transaction to Ethereum as `calldata`.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] `calldata` costs are currently governed by EIP-1559 (opens in a new tab), which stipulates a cost of 16 gas for non-zero bytes and 4 gas for zero bytes of `calldata`, respectively.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] The cost paid on each transaction is influenced by how much `calldata` needs to be posted onchain for it.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] **L2 operator fees**: This is the amount paid to the rollup operator as compensation for computational costs incurred in processing transactions, much like transaction "priority fees (tips)" on Ethereum Mainnet.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] **Proof generation and verification**: ZK-rollup operators must produce validity proofs for transaction batches, which is resource-intensive.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] Verifying zero-knowledge proofs on Mainnet also costs gas (~ 500,000 gas).
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] Apart from batching transactions, ZK-rollups reduce fees for users by compressing transaction data.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] You can see a real-time overview (opens in a new tab) of how it costs to use Ethereum ZK-rollups.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] ZK-rollups extend the throughput on Ethereum’s base layer by taking computation offchain, but the real boost for scaling comes from compressing transaction data.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] Ethereum’s block size limits the data each block can hold and, by extension, the number of transactions processed per block.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] By compressing transaction-related data, ZK-rollups significantly increase the number of transactions processed per block.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] ZK-rollups can compress transaction data better than optimistic rollups since they don't have to post all the data required to validate each transaction.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] They only have to post the minimal data required to rebuild the latest state of accounts and balances on the rollup.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] An advantage of zero-knowledge proofs is that proofs can verify other proofs.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] For example, a single ZK-SNARK can verify other ZK-SNARKs.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] Such "proof-of-proofs" are called recursive proofs and dramatically increase throughput on ZK-rollups.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] Currently, validity proofs are generated on a block-by-block basis and submitted to the L1 contract for verification.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] However, verifying single block proofs limits the throughput that ZK-rollups can achieve since only one block can be finalized when the operator submits a proof.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] Recursive proofs, however, make it possible to finalize several blocks with one validity proof.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] This is because the proving circuit recursively aggregates multiple block proofs until one final proof is created.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] The L2 operator submits this recursive proof, and if the contract accepts it, all the relevant blocks will be finalized instantly.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] With recursive proofs, the number of ZK-rollup transactions that can be finalized on Ethereum at intervals increases.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] The projects below use zkEVM technology to build Layer 2 rollups.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/scaling-zk-rollups] , which would enable validators to verify Ethereum blocks without re-executing transactions.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zcash] Launched in October 2016, Zcash was developed by cryptographers at Johns Hopkins University and MIT and derived its code from bitcoin.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zcash] Zcash was one of the first large-scale implementations of zero-knowledge proofs outside of academia.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zcash] Zcash is modeled on bitcoin, sharing its proof-of-work consensus mechanism.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zcash] In 2016, Tom Robinson, co-founder of blockchain tracing firm Elliptic, told CNBC that Zcash appeared to have achieved a high level of anonymity.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zcash] Zcash supports two types of addresses: transparent addresses, which function similarly to bitcoin addresses with publicly visible transactions, and shielded addresses, which use zero-knowledge proofs to encrypt transaction data.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zcash] Shielded transactions can be verified as valid without revealing the sender, recipient, or amount transferred.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zcash] Users can transact between the two types, allowing funds to move between the transparent and shielded pools.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zcash] This optional privacy model is intended to preserve fungibility, allowing units of the currency to be treated equally regardless of their transaction history.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zcash] Users also have the option to share private viewing keys, allowing designated third parties to see their transaction details for auditing purposes.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zcash] A 2018 study found that while it is possible to use Zcash privately, the anonymity set of the shielded pool could be reduced through heuristics-based analysis of usage patterns.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zcash] The analysis predates subsequent protocol upgrades to the shielded transaction system.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zcash] In 2022, journalist Andy Greenberg described Zcash's shielded transactions as "provably inaccessible" to surveillance and said he had not seen evidence that its anonymity could be compromised.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zcash] Development work on Zcash began in 2013 by Johns Hopkins University professor Matthew Green and his graduate students Ian Miers and Christina Garman, who developed the Zerocoin protocol.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zcash] They subsequently joined forces with a team of cryptographers including Alessandro Chiesa and Madars Virza from MIT, and Eli Ben-Sasson from the Technion and Eran Tromer from Tel Aviv University, who had developed a more efficient variant called zk-SNARKs.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zcash] The development was completed by the for-profit Zcash Company, led by Zooko Wilcox, a Colorado based computer security specialist.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zcash] The Zcash Company raised over $3 million from investors including Naval Ravikant.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zcash] Zcash was first mined in late October 2016.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zcash] To generate revenue, 10% of all coins mined for the first four years were automatically distributed to the Zcash Company and the Zcash Foundation.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zcash] The instantiation of the Zcash network required the creation of a master private key.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zcash] To ensure privacy, this private key must later be destroyed, otherwise counterfeit Zcash coins could be generated.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zcash] To maximize the chance that no one person could obtain the private key, software was written which allowed individuals from six different locations to collaboratively generate the private key, use it to instantiate Zcash, and then destroy the computers used in the process afterwards.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zcash] In 2019, Electric Coin Company researcher Sean Bowe discovered Halo, a technique for generating zero-knowledge proofs without requiring a trusted setup ceremony.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zcash] This eliminated the need for the elaborate multi-party ceremonies used at launch.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zcash] In 2018, *MIT Technology Review* named Zcash co-founder Alessandro Chiesa, an assistant professor at the University of California, Berkeley, to its Innovators Under 35 list for his work on the zero-knowledge proof technology underlying the cryptocurrency.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zcash] In 2022, Edward Snowden revealed that he had participated in the creation of Zcash under the pseudonym "John Dobbertin." Other participants in the ceremony included Peter Todd, a Bitcoin Core developer.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zcash] On February 21, 2019, the "Zcash Company" announced a rebranding as the Electric Coin Company (ECC).
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zcash] In 2020, the Electric Coin Company transitioned to nonprofit ownership, becoming a wholly owned subsidiary of the Bootstrap Project, a 501(c)(3) organization.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zcash] In September 2023, a mining pool named ViaBTC had seized control of over half the hashing power on Zcash.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zcash] This 51% dominance raised worries about a 51% attack, where they could potentially manipulate transactions and harm the network.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zcash] In response, Coinbase placed Zcash markets into "limit-only" mode in an effort to prevent significant price swings.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zcash] In November 2025, Cameron Winklevoss and Tyler Winklevoss invested $50 million to launch Cypherpunk Technologies, a digital-asset treasury company focused on the cryptocurrency.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zcash] Securities and Exchange Commission closed a probe into Zcash.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zcash] In April 2026, Foundry, one of the largest bitcoin mining pool operators, launched a dedicated Zcash mining pool.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zcash] In 2017, JPMorgan Chase integrated Zcash's zero-knowledge proof technology into its enterprise blockchain platform Quorum to enable confidential transactions for business clients.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zcash] *Fortune* reported that Zcash's fundamental technology would be added to the Ethereum network.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zcash] In late 2017, Grayscale Investments launched a Zcash investment fund, which is the company's third dedicated cryptocurrency fund after bitcoin and Ethereum Classic.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zcash] In 2026, Grayscale filed with regulators to convert the fund into an exchange-traded fund.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zcash] In May 2018, the New York State Department of Financial Services approved Zcash for trading on Gemini.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zcash] The Freedom of the Press Foundation, the Human Rights Foundation, and the Electronic Frontier Foundation have accepted Zcash donations.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zcash] In 2017, the European Union's law enforcement agency Europol flagged Zcash, along with bitcoin and Monero, for potential use in internet-based crime.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zcash] The same report noted that Zcash was not known to have a significant criminal following.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zcash] In 2018, several Japanese exchanges delisted Zcash and other privacy-focused cryptocurrencies citing regulatory pressure following a major exchange hack; the delisted coins had not been involved in the hack.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zcash] A 2023 analysis of cryptocurrency and crime similarly found that Zcash "featured very rarely on the dark web" compared to Monero.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] The intuition behind the nontriviality of zero-knowledge proofs is that it is trivial to prove possession of the relevant information simply by revealing it; the hard part is to prove this possession without revealing this information (or any aspect of it whatsoever).
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Zero-knowledge proofs can be interactive, meaning that the prover and verifier exchange messages according to some protocol, or noninteractive, meaning that the verifier is convinced by a single prover message and no other communication is needed.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] In the standard model, interaction is required, except for trivial proofs of BPP problems.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] In the common random string and random oracle models, non-interactive zero-knowledge proofs exist.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] The Fiat–Shamir heuristic can be used to transform certain interactive zero-knowledge proofs into noninteractive ones.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] One example of a math-free zero-knowledge proof is if Peggy wants to prove to Victor that she has drawn a red card from a standard deck of 52 playing cards, without revealing which specific red card she holds.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Victor observes Peggy draw a card at random from the shuffled deck, but she keeps the card face-down so he cannot see it.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] To prove her card is red without revealing its identity, Peggy takes the remaining 51 cards from the deck and systematically shows Victor all 26 black cards (the 13 spades and 13 clubs) one by one, placing them face-up on the table.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Since a standard deck contains exactly 26 red cards and 26 black cards, and Peggy has demonstrated that all the black cards remain in the deck, Victor can conclude with certainty that Peggy's hidden card must be red.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] This proof is zero-knowledge because Victor learns only that Peggy's card is red, but gains no information about whether it is a heart or diamond, or which specific red card she holds.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] The proof would be equally convincing whether Peggy held the Ace of Hearts or the Two of Diamonds.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Furthermore, even if the interaction were recorded, the recording would not reveal Peggy's specific card to future observers, maintaining the zero-knowledge property.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] If Peggy were lying and actually held a black card, she would be unable to produce all 26 black cards from the remaining deck, making deception impossible.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] This demonstrates the soundness of the proof system.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] This type of physical zero-knowledge proof using standard playing cards belongs to a broader class of card-based cryptographic protocols that allow participants to perform secure computations using everyday objects.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Another well-known example of a zero-knowledge proof is the "Where's Waldo" example.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] In this example, the prover has a page from a *Where's Waldo?* children's book, which shows many hundreds of cartoon people, where only one of them is the visually distinctive character of Waldo.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] The prover wants to prove to the verifier that they know where Waldo is on the page, without revealing his location to the verifier.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] The prover starts by taking a large black board with a small hole in it, the size of Waldo.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] The board is twice the size of the book in both directions, so the verifier cannot see where on the page the prover is placing it.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] The prover then places the board over the page so that Waldo is in the hole.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] The verifier can now look through the hole and see Waldo, but cannot see any other part of the page.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Therefore, the prover has proven to the verifier that they know where Waldo is, without revealing any other information about his location.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] This example is not a perfect zero-knowledge proof, because the prover does reveal some information about Waldo's location, such as his body position.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] However, it is a decent illustration of the basic concept of a zero-knowledge proof.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Peggy takes either path A or B, while Victor waits outside.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Peggy reliably appears at the exit Victor names.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] There is a well-known story presenting the fundamental ideas of zero-knowledge proofs, first published in 1990 by Jean-Jacques Quisquater and others in their paper "How to Explain Zero-Knowledge Protocols to Your Children".
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] The two parties in the zero-knowledge proof story are Peggy as the prover of the statement, and Victor, the verifier of the statement.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] In this story, Peggy has uncovered the secret word used to open a magic door in a cave.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] The cave is shaped like a ring, with the entrance on one side and the magic door blocking the opposite side.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Victor wants to know whether Peggy knows the secret word; but Peggy, being a very private person, does not want to reveal her knowledge (the secret word) to Victor or to reveal the fact of her knowledge to the world in general.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] They label the paths from the entrance A and B.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] First, Victor waits outside the cave as Peggy goes in.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Peggy takes either path A or B; Victor is not allowed to see which path she takes.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Then, Victor enters the cave and shouts the name of the path he wants her to use to return, either A or B, chosen at random.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Providing she really does know the magic word, this is easy: she opens the door, if necessary, and returns along the desired path.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] However, suppose she did not know the word.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Then, she would only be able to return by the named path if Victor were to give the name of the same path by which she had entered.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Since Victor would choose A or B at random, she would have a 50% chance of guessing correctly.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] If they were to repeat this trick many times, say 20 times in a row, her chance of successfully anticipating all of Victor's requests would be reduced to 1 in 220, or 9.54 × 10−7.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Thus, if Peggy repeatedly appears at the exit Victor names, then he can conclude that it is extremely probable that Peggy does, in fact, know the secret word.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] With respect to third-party observers: even if Victor is wearing a hidden camera that records the whole transaction, the only thing the camera will record is in one case Victor shouting "A!" and Peggy appearing at A or in the other case Victor shouting "B!" and Peggy appearing at B.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] A recording of this type would be trivial for any two people to fake (requiring only that Peggy and Victor agree beforehand on the sequence of As and Bs that Victor will shout).
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Such a recording will certainly never be convincing to anyone but the original participants.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] In fact, even a person who was present as an observer at the original experiment should be unconvinced, since Victor and Peggy could have orchestrated the whole "experiment" from start to finish.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Further, if Victor chooses his As and Bs by flipping a coin on-camera, this protocol loses its zero-knowledge property; the on-camera coin flip would probably be convincing to any person watching the recording later.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Thus, although this does not reveal the secret word to Victor, it does make it possible for Victor to convince the world in general that Peggy has that knowledge—counter to Peggy's stated wishes.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] However, digital cryptography generally "flips coins" by relying on a pseudo-random number generator, which is akin to a coin with a fixed pattern of heads and tails known only to the coin's owner.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] If Victor's coin behaved this way, then again it would be possible for Victor and Peggy to have faked the experiment, so using a pseudo-random number generator would not reveal Peggy's knowledge to the world in the same way that using a flipped coin would.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Peggy could prove to Victor that she knows the magic word, without revealing it to him, in a single trial.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] If both Victor and Peggy go together to the mouth of the cave, Victor can watch Peggy go in through A and come out through B.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] This would prove with certainty that Peggy knows the magic word, without revealing the magic word to Victor.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] However, such a proof could be observed by a third party, or recorded by Victor and such a proof would be convincing to anybody.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] In other words, Peggy could not refute such proof by claiming she colluded with Victor, and she is therefore no longer in control of who is aware of her knowledge.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Imagine Victor is red-green color-blind (while Peggy is not) and Peggy has two balls: one red and one green, but otherwise identical.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] To Victor, the balls seem completely identical.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Victor is skeptical that the balls are actually distinguishable.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Peggy wants to *prove to Victor that the balls are in fact differently colored*, but nothing else.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] In particular, Peggy does not want to reveal which ball is the red one and which is the green.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Here is the proof system: Peggy gives the two balls to Victor and he puts them behind his back.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Next, he takes one of the balls and brings it out from behind his back and displays it.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] He then places it behind his back again and then chooses to reveal just one of the two balls, picking one of the two at random with equal probability.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] He will ask Peggy, "Did I switch the ball?" This whole procedure is then repeated as often as necessary.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] By looking at the balls' colors, Peggy can, of course, say with certainty whether or not he switched them.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] On the other hand, if the balls were the same color and hence indistinguishable, Peggy's ability to determine whether a switch occurred would be no better than random guessing.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Since the probability that Peggy would have randomly succeeded at identifying each switch/non-switch is 50%, the probability of having randomly succeeded at *all* switch/non-switches approaches zero.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Over multiple trials, the success rate would statistically converge to 50%, and Peggy could not achieve a performance significantly better than chance.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] If Peggy and Victor repeat this "proof" multiple times (e.g.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] 20 times), Victor should become convinced that the balls are indeed differently colored.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] The above proof is *zero-knowledge* because Victor never learns which ball is green and which is red; indeed, he gains no knowledge about how to distinguish the balls.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] **Soundness**: if the statement is false, then no cheating prover can convince an honest verifier that it is true, except with some small probability.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] **Zero-knowledge**: if the statement is true, then no verifier learns anything other than the fact that the statement is true.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] In other words, just knowing the statement (not the secret) is sufficient to imagine a scenario showing that the prover knows the secret.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] This is formalized by showing that every verifier has some *simulator* that, given only the statement to be proved (and no access to the prover), can produce a transcript that "looks like" an interaction between an honest prover and the verifier in question.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] The first two of these are properties of more general interactive proof systems.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] The third is what makes the proof zero-knowledge.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Zero-knowledge proofs are not proofs in the mathematical sense of the term because there is some small probability, the *soundness error*, that a cheating prover will be able to convince the verifier of a false statement.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] In other words, zero-knowledge proofs are probabilistic "proofs" rather than deterministic proofs.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] However, there are techniques to decrease the soundness error to negligibly small values (for example, guessing correctly on a hundred or thousand binary decisions has a 1/2100 or 1/21000 soundness error, respectively.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] As the number of bits increases, the soundness error decreases toward zero).
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] A formal definition of zero-knowledge must use some computational model, the most common one being that of a Turing machine.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] The prover P is modeled as having unlimited computation power (in practice, P usually is a probabilistic Turing machine).
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Intuitively, the definition states that an interactive proof system (*P*,*V*) is zero-knowledge if for any verifier ${\hat {V}}$ there exists an efficient simulator S (depending on ${\hat {V}}$ ) that can reproduce the conversation between P and ${\hat {V}}$ on any given input.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] The auxiliary string z in the definition plays the role of "prior knowledge" (including the random coins of ${\hat {V}}$ ).
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] The definition implies that ${\hat {V}}$ cannot use any prior knowledge string z to mine information out of its conversation with P, because if S is also given this prior knowledge then it can reproduce the conversation between ${\hat {V}}$ and P just as before.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] The definition given is that of perfect zero-knowledge.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Computational zero-knowledge is obtained by requiring that the views of the verifier ${\hat {V}}$ and the simulator are only computationally indistinguishable, given the auxiliary string.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] These ideas can be applied to a more realistic cryptography application.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Peggy wants to prove to Victor that she knows the discrete logarithm of a given value in a given group.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] For example, given a value y, a large prime p, and a generator g , she wants to prove that she knows a value x such that *g**x* ≡ *y* (mod *p*), without revealing x.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] The protocol proceeds as follows: in each round, Peggy generates a random number r, computes *C* = *g**r* mod *p* and discloses this to Victor.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] After receiving C, Victor randomly issues one of the following two requests: he either requests that Peggy discloses the value of r, or the value of (*x* + *r*) mod (*p* − 1).
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Victor can verify either answer; if he requested r, he can then compute *g**r* mod *p* and verify that it matches C.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] If he requested (*x* + *r*) mod (*p* − 1), then he can verify that C is consistent with this, by computing *g*(*x* + *r*) mod (*p* − 1) mod *p* and verifying that it matches (*C* · *y*) mod *p*.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] If Peggy indeed knows the value of x, then she can respond to either one of Victor's possible challenges.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] On the other hand, if she knows that Victor will request (*x* + *r*) mod (*p* − 1), then she picks a random value *r*′, computes *C*′ ≡ *g**r*′ · (*g**x*)−1 mod *p*, and discloses *C*′ to Victor as the value of C that he is expecting.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] When Victor challenges her to reveal (*x* + *r*) mod (*p* − 1), she reveals *r*′, for which Victor will verify consistency, since he will in turn compute *g**r*′ mod *p*, which matches *C*′ · *y*, since Peggy multiplied by the modular multiplicative inverse of y.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] However, if in either one of the above scenarios Victor issues a challenge other than the one she was expecting and for which she manufactured the result, then she will be unable to respond to the challenge under the assumption of infeasibility of solving the discrete log for this group.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] If she picked r and disclosed *C* = *g**r* mod *p*, then she will be unable to produce a valid (*x* + *r*) mod (*p* − 1) that would pass Victor's verification, given that she does not know x.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Thus, a cheating prover has a 0.5 probability of successfully cheating in one round.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] By executing a large-enough number of rounds, the probability of a cheating prover succeeding can be made arbitrarily low.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] To show that the above interactive proof gives zero knowledge other than the fact that Peggy knows x, one can use similar arguments as used in the above proof of completeness and soundness.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Specifically, a simulator, say Simon, who does not know x, can simulate the exchange between Peggy and Victor by the following procedure.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Firstly, Simon randomly flips a fair coin.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] If the result is "heads", then he picks a random value r, computes *C* = *g**r* mod *p*, and discloses C as if it is a message from Peggy to Victor.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Then Simon also outputs a message "request the value of r" as if it is sent from Victor to Peggy, and immediately outputs the value of r as if it is sent from Peggy to Victor.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] On the other hand, if the coin flipping result is "tails", then Simon picks a random number *r*′, computes *C*′ = *g**r*′ · *y*−1 mod *p*, and discloses *C*′ as if it is a message from Peggy to Victor.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Then Simon outputs "request the value of (*x* + *r*) mod (*p* − 1)" as if it is a message from Victor to Peggy.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Finally, Simon outputs the value of *r*′ as if it is the response from Peggy back to Victor.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] By the previous arguments when proving the completeness and soundness, the interactive communication simulated by Simon is indistinguishable from the true correspondence between Peggy and Victor.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] The zero-knowledge property is thus guaranteed.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] The following scheme is due to Manuel Blum.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] In this scenario, Peggy knows a Hamiltonian cycle for a large graph G.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Victor knows G but not the cycle (e.g., Peggy has generated G and revealed it to him.) Finding a Hamiltonian cycle given a large graph is believed to be computationally infeasible, since its corresponding decision version is known to be NP-complete.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Peggy will prove that she knows the cycle without simply revealing it (perhaps Victor is interested in buying it but wants verification first, or maybe Peggy is the only one who knows this information and is proving her identity to Victor).
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] It is important that the commitment to the graph be such that Victor can verify, in the second case, that the cycle is really made of edges from H.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] This can be done by, for example, committing to every edge (or lack thereof) separately.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] If Peggy does know a Hamiltonian cycle in G, then she can easily satisfy Victor's demand for either the graph isomorphism producing H from G (which she had committed to in the first step) or a Hamiltonian cycle in H (which she can construct by applying the isomorphism to the cycle in G).
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Peggy's answers do not reveal the original Hamiltonian cycle in G.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] In each round, Victor will learn only H's isomorphism to G or a Hamiltonian cycle in H.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] He would need both answers for a single H to discover the cycle in G, so the information remains unknown as long as Peggy can generate a distinct H every round.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] If Peggy does not know of a Hamiltonian cycle in G, but somehow knew in advance what Victor would ask to see each round, then she could cheat.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] For example, if Peggy knew ahead of time that Victor would ask to see the Hamiltonian cycle in H, then she could generate a Hamiltonian cycle for an unrelated graph.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Similarly, if Peggy knew in advance that Victor would ask to see the isomorphism then she could simply generate an isomorphic graph H (in which she also does not know a Hamiltonian cycle).
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Victor could simulate the protocol by himself (without Peggy) because he knows what he will ask to see.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Therefore, Victor gains no information about the Hamiltonian cycle in G from the information revealed in each round.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] If Peggy does not know the information, then she can guess which question Victor will ask and generate either a graph isomorphic to G or a Hamiltonian cycle for an unrelated graph, but since she does not know a Hamiltonian cycle for G, she cannot do both.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] With this guesswork, her chance of fooling Victor is 2−*n*, where n is the number of rounds.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] For all realistic purposes, it is infeasibly difficult to defeat a zero-knowledge proof with a reasonable number of rounds in this way.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Zero-knowledge proof schemes can be constructed from various cryptographic primitives, such as hash-based cryptography, pairing-based cryptography, multi-party computation, or lattice-based cryptography.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Generally, zero-knowledge proofs are used within protocols to enforce honest behavior while maintaining privacy.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Roughly, the idea is to force a user to prove, using a zero-knowledge proof, that their behavior is correct according to the protocol.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Research in zero-knowledge proofs has been motivated by authentication systems where one party wants to prove its identity to a second party via some secret information (such as a password) but does not want the second party to learn anything about this secret.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] This is called a "zero-knowledge proof of knowledge".
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] However, a password is typically too small or insufficiently random to be used in many schemes for zero-knowledge proofs of knowledge.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] A zero-knowledge password proof is a special kind of zero-knowledge proof of knowledge that addresses the limited size of passwords.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] In April 2015, the one-out-of-many proofs protocol (a Sigma protocol) was introduced.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] In August 2021, Cloudflare, an American web infrastructure and security company, decided to use the one-out-of-many proofs mechanism for private web verification using vendor hardware.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] In 2016, the Princeton Plasma Physics Laboratory and Princeton University demonstrated a technique that may have applicability to future nuclear disarmament talks.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] It would allow inspectors to confirm whether or not an object is indeed a nuclear weapon without recording, sharing, or revealing the internal workings, which might be secret.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Zero-knowledge proofs were applied in the Zerocoin and Zerocash protocols, which culminated in the birth of Zcoin (later rebranded as Firo in 2020) and Zcash cryptocurrencies in 2016.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Zerocoin has a built-in mixing model that does not trust any peers or centralized mixing providers to ensure anonymity.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Users can transact in a base currency and can cycle the currency into and out of Zerocoins.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] The Zerocash protocol uses a similar model (a variant known as a non-interactive zero-knowledge proof) except that it can obscure the transaction amount, while Zerocoin cannot.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Bulletproofs are an improvement from non-interactive zero-knowledge proofs where a trusted setup is not needed.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Because of asymmetric signatures in documents such as passports and emails, zero knowledge proofs can be made of people's identities in order to privately verify information about themselves.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] For instance, you can prove that you are over 18 to a website, without revealing other details like your exact name or country of origin, by proving in zero knowledge that you own a passport signed by a valid government key for an age value over 18.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] By similarly making zero-knowledge proofs of the DKIM signatures of their emails, people can prove that they ordered or transferred a domain or concert ticket, own some handle on a social media service, or ordered something on an e-commerce service.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] The zero knowledge property allows people to keep their own identity and email address private while doing so.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] These can be used to enable private and fair elections, low-fee secondary marketplaces, and whistleblowing services.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] A related line of work applies zero-knowledge proofs to database analytics via so-called zero-knowledge "coprocessors": off-chain systems that execute queries and return both the result and a proof that the computation was performed correctly on untampered data.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Academic prototypes have shown how to produce ZK proofs for ad-hoc SQL queries while hiding inputs and guaranteeing correctness of the result (e.g., ZKSQL).
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Zero-knowledge proofs were first conceived in 1985 by Shafi Goldwasser, Silvio Micali, and Charles Rackoff in their paper "The Knowledge Complexity of Interactive Proof-Systems".
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] This paper introduced the IP hierarchy of interactive proof systems (*see interactive proof system*) and conceived the concept of *knowledge complexity*, a measurement of the amount of knowledge about the proof transferred from the prover to the verifier.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] They also gave the first zero-knowledge proof for a concrete problem, that of deciding quadratic nonresidues mod *m*.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Together with a paper by László Babai and Shlomo Moran, this landmark paper invented interactive proof systems, for which all five authors won the first Gödel Prize in 1993.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] The quadratic nonresidue problem has both an NP and a co-NP algorithm, and so lies in the intersection of NP and co-NP.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] This was also true of several other problems for which zero-knowledge proofs were subsequently discovered, such as an unpublished proof system by Oded Goldreich verifying that a two-prime modulus is not a Blum integer.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Oded Goldreich, Silvio Micali, and Avi Wigderson took this one step further, showing that, assuming the existence of unbreakable encryption, one can create a zero-knowledge proof system for the NP-complete graph coloring problem with three colors.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Since every problem in NP can be efficiently reduced to this problem, this means that, under this assumption, all problems in NP have zero-knowledge proofs.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] The reason for the assumption is that, as in the above example, their protocols require encryption.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] A commonly cited sufficient condition for the existence of unbreakable encryption is the existence of one-way functions, but it is conceivable that some physical means might also achieve it.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] On top of this, they also showed that the graph nonisomorphism problem, the complement of the graph isomorphism problem, has a zero-knowledge proof.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] This problem is in co-NP, but is not currently known to be in either NP or any practical class.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Not liking to make unnecessary assumptions, many theorists sought a way to eliminate the necessity of one way functions.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] One way this was done was with *multi-prover interactive proof systems* (see interactive proof system), which have multiple independent provers instead of only one, allowing the verifier to "cross-examine" the provers in isolation to avoid being misled.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] It can be shown that, without any intractability assumptions, all languages in NP have zero-knowledge proofs in such a system.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] It turns out that, in an Internet-like setting, where multiple protocols may be executed concurrently, building zero-knowledge proofs is more challenging.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] The line of research investigating concurrent zero-knowledge proofs was initiated by the work of Dwork, Naor, and Sahai.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] One particular development along these lines has been the development of witness-indistinguishable proof protocols.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] The property of witness-indistinguishability is related to that of zero-knowledge, yet witness-indistinguishable protocols do not suffer from the same problems of concurrent execution.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Another variant of zero-knowledge proofs are non-interactive zero-knowledge proofs.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Blum, Feldman, and Micali showed that a common random string shared between the prover and the verifier is enough to achieve computational zero-knowledge without requiring interaction.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] A list of zero-knowledge proof protocols and libraries is provided below along with comparisons based on *transparency*, *universality*, *plausible post-quantum security*, and *programming paradigm*.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] A transparent protocol is one that does not require any trusted setup and uses public randomness.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] A universal protocol is one that does not require a separate trusted setup for each circuit.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Finally, a plausibly post-quantum protocol is one that is not susceptible to known attacks involving quantum algorithms.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] While zero-knowledge proofs offer a secure way to verify information, the arithmetic circuits that implement them must be carefully designed.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] If these circuits lack sufficient constraints, they may introduce subtle yet critical security vulnerabilities.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] One of the most common classes of vulnerabilities in these systems is under-constrained logic, where insufficient constraints allow a malicious prover to produce a proof for an incorrect statement that still passes verification.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] A 2024 systematization of known attacks found that approximately 96% of documented circuit-layer bugs in SNARK-based systems were due to under-constrained circuits.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] These vulnerabilities often arise during the translation of high-level logic into low-level constraint systems, particularly when using domain-specific languages such as Circom or Gnark.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Recent research has demonstrated that formally proving determinism – ensuring that a circuit's outputs are uniquely determined by its inputs – can eliminate entire classes of these vulnerabilities.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Zero-knowledge virtual machines (zkVMs) are general-purpose virtual computers designed to execute code and generate zero-knowledge proofs that verify off-chain, without revealing private inputs, that the code ran correctly and produced the claimed result.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] A proof is a compact, structured binary file that can be efficiently checked by anyone using the zkVM's verifier tool without re-running the original computation.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] zkVMs have both development and security benefits.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Using a zkVM, developers can execute and verify complex computations off-chain, avoiding high on-chain "gas costs" (blockchain processing fees) and maintaining the privacy of code or data.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Several recently developed zkVMs, such as those developed by RISC Zero and Succinct Labs, support the RISC-V instruction set, which allows programmers to write code in mainstream programming languages like Rust instead of using a domain-specific circuit language such as Circom.
[src:zero-knowledge-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Other zkVMs take different approaches, targeting WebAssembly (WASM) or implementing custom instruction sets optimized for zero-knowledge performance or integration with particular blockchain environments.
